WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.480
So, my name is Hubert, and I'm a visual designer at Appsilon.

00:00:03.480 --> 00:00:05.800
And today we're gonna talk about Art of R packages

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:08.420
and how to forge community around them.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:13.500
I am an author of Rhinoverse stickers,

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:16.480
and as well as Nest stickers.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:20.520
So I got a little bit of experience in design.

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:22.840
So let's go ahead.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:26.059
Our main topic will be community and design

00:00:26.059 --> 00:00:27.660
and how to blend it together.

00:00:30.219 --> 00:00:33.480
So let's start with what exactly is community.

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:38.599
According to Wikipedia, community is a social unit

00:00:38.599 --> 00:00:41.000
with shared significant characteristic.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.200
And it makes sense, it's probably true.

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:49.480
But I think each of us understand it in its own way.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:52.439
Everybody experience community a little bit different.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.400
So for me, for example,

00:00:56.400 --> 00:00:59.080
community is people who share experience

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:00.980
and emotion on the same topic.

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:05.860
And I'm gonna be a little bit nerdy here.

00:01:05.860 --> 00:01:08.919
So after work, I really like to play games.

00:01:08.919 --> 00:01:10.620
I like to call the game on myself.

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:14.160
Yeah, here you can see some popular games

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:15.500
like Bottles Game 3,

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:18.180
which I spend definitely too much time on.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:20.720
Some other really tough one,

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:23.680
and The Witcher 3, which I cannot resist to put here.

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:25.480
It's our small Polish pride.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:30.400
And so, but what those games are going in common?

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:35.120
Basically, without a community of those games,

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:37.879
you are missing really important part of experience

00:01:37.879 --> 00:01:40.440
because the games are really big

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:42.959
and you can like miss a lot of things.

00:01:42.959 --> 00:01:46.320
So for example, you can miss a secret way

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:48.160
that will save you time.

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:49.400
And you can find a way,

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:51.760
you can find the answer in a community.

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:53.440
Maybe you can also miss like an opinion

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:55.440
about some lower character on events

00:01:56.199 --> 00:01:57.760
or maybe you cannot spot like the weapon

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:59.400
cannot solve your problem later.

00:02:00.720 --> 00:02:03.680
So solving problems together,

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:06.599
which require experience to solve them

00:02:06.599 --> 00:02:08.039
and share your opinion,

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:11.559
which always involve emotion, drives the community.

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:15.839
If only there was another community like that.

00:02:16.759 --> 00:02:19.440
I wonder, and I think I got an idea.

00:02:20.479 --> 00:02:21.679
Yeah, there we go.

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:23.199
Our lovely R community.

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:27.320
So, and this is a small comparison

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:28.880
because instead of secret way

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:30.679
that will save you time in a game,

00:02:30.679 --> 00:02:33.360
you can find in our community a tip or shortcut

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:34.600
that will save you time.

00:02:35.679 --> 00:02:37.720
Or for example, you can share opinion

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:39.559
about some community events

00:02:39.559 --> 00:02:42.520
and it's gonna help you decide if it's worth going for it.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:46.160
Or instead of the weapon,

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:49.119
you can find a package that will solve your problems later.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:51.279
And speaking about hexes,

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.240
do you ever wonder why we do collect things like at all?

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.039
So basically people from beginning of time,

00:03:00.039 --> 00:03:02.320
they just love collecting things,

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:05.279
but they're doing it for preserving memories,

00:03:05.279 --> 00:03:08.639
express the identity, finding the joy

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:10.199
or connect with other peoples.

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:13.600
So as you can see,

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:16.199
we can collect a lot of different things

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:18.080
like coins, crystals, stones,

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:20.000
instruments, or even Pokemons.

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:24.240
People have always loved collecting things,

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.639
especially the shiny one.

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:27.960
Wink, wink to everybody.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.520
So the question is how hex stickers can build our community?

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:38.479
Well, here you got a bunch of photos of people

00:03:38.479 --> 00:03:40.240
enjoying the environment of hexes.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:46.160
As well, I can show you that hexes are not only the stickers

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:50.759
but you can put it as a pattern on a sport clothes

00:03:50.759 --> 00:03:53.360
or as a decoration on a cake.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:56.199
And I think my favorite one, which is the jewelry,

00:03:56.199 --> 00:03:58.320
as you can see, there's small hexes with the colors

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.880
according to the stickers in behind.

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:03.279
So this is cool.

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:09.679
So to sum it up, hexes build a community

00:04:09.679 --> 00:04:11.520
by connecting people together.

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:12.880
And this is the answer.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:14.479
We love them.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:19.320
So question now, if we know that people love

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:22.519
to collect things, especially the shiny one,

00:04:22.519 --> 00:04:24.359
and the question is how to design a hex

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:26.559
that will be recognizable and well-made.

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:29.079
And this is the second part of the presentation

00:04:29.079 --> 00:04:31.720
where we're gonna talk strictly about the design.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:35.640
So there are three rules, symbol, colors, and details.

00:04:37.079 --> 00:04:39.000
First of them is capture the essence

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.559
of a package in one symbol.

00:04:41.559 --> 00:04:42.559
And it's really important.

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:44.720
And I will show you a few examples.

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:46.760
For example, in the nest one.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:50.519
So what I was told that the nest hex

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:52.760
should be about nesting thing inside

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:55.399
and also be related to bird nest.

00:04:55.399 --> 00:04:57.040
So this is what I did.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:04:59.920
You can see like top view of the nest.

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:04.920
And also I make this one element on the right.

00:05:05.079 --> 00:05:06.959
And then by repeating itself,

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:09.440
I created the whole image of a nest from the top.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:13.760
Another one, and the side note,

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:15.320
I am not the author of this hex,

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:16.519
but I really love this one.

00:05:16.519 --> 00:05:18.519
And I will try to do an interpretation,

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:20.119
how it was made, but I am not sure

00:05:20.119 --> 00:05:22.399
if it's actually what author got in mind.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:28.519
So PUR itself, from what I know in simple terms,

00:05:28.519 --> 00:05:30.359
is about the iteration.

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:33.279
So we got a cat made by pencil.

00:05:33.279 --> 00:05:38.079
And the word PUR is basically a tonal voice that cat makes.

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:40.679
Then in the word, you got triple R,

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:43.359
which is about the iteration.

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:45.559
R, R, R, and R community.

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:49.000
But about the pencil,

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.920
if you want to achieve really good quality sketch

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:54.880
when drawing with pencil,

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:58.320
you need to iterate it a lot of times.

00:05:58.320 --> 00:05:59.880
So as you can see,

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:02.720
it's all coming together into one symbol.

00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:03.839
That just makes sense.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:06.279
I hope I get it right.

00:06:06.399 --> 00:06:07.920
We got also the rhino,

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:10.200
which is package that will help you build

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:12.799
a stable application

00:06:12.799 --> 00:06:15.040
and well-structured organization of the files.

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:17.600
So I choose the rhino animal

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.279
because it's a symbol of strength and stability

00:06:21.279 --> 00:06:26.279
and all the geometric shapes of the logo

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:30.880
to just emphasize the well-structured inside.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:34.480
And here you got the cat.

00:06:35.359 --> 00:06:38.760
And here you got like a smaller workflow,

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:40.839
how I work on the stickers, how I made them.

00:06:40.839 --> 00:06:42.920
So basically I start with reference.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:44.959
Then I get the quick sketch on the paper.

00:06:44.959 --> 00:06:48.160
Some first shapes in usually vector program,

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:49.679
advanced shaping.

00:06:49.679 --> 00:06:51.440
Then we've got the black and white version

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:53.720
and some details and colors in the end.

00:06:55.359 --> 00:06:56.239
All right.

00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:59.839
Second rule, evoke emotion with colors.

00:07:00.839 --> 00:07:04.359
As you may know, some colors evoke different emotion.

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:08.559
If somebody wants, you can take a photo of it.

00:07:08.559 --> 00:07:13.119
For example, red one can evoke a new strength or speed.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:16.200
And this is what I did here.

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:18.000
Shiny Benchmark is basically all about

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:19.760
the testing and speed.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:20.600
And as you can see,

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:22.119
the left one is the original one

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:24.679
and the right one is special for this presentation.

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:27.399
I just want to show you the difference in colors

00:07:27.399 --> 00:07:29.359
and how it matters

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.359
because you can feel on the left

00:07:32.359 --> 00:07:35.160
that the red giving this power to it.

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:37.959
And the green one, there's something over the green one.

00:07:39.200 --> 00:07:43.239
We got also churn, which in this example,

00:07:43.239 --> 00:07:46.160
the most important thing was the graph on the wings.

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.760
You can see the red and the green line.

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:50.920
But when you take the color, you cannot see them.

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:52.679
It just doesn't make sense anymore.

00:07:53.679 --> 00:07:56.839
And I think this one is the best one example in colors.

00:07:56.839 --> 00:07:59.799
Tidyverse is about showing the space in the galaxy,

00:07:59.799 --> 00:08:01.880
you know, all the stars and everything.

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:04.559
But when you invert the colors, it's not a space.

00:08:04.559 --> 00:08:07.160
It's like some dirty tile on surfing.

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:10.959
So this is why the color is really important.

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:14.359
All right, the third one, the details.

00:08:14.359 --> 00:08:15.760
The details for more context.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:20.079
Speaking of Tidyverse, I don't know if you notice,

00:08:20.079 --> 00:08:22.480
but those small dots are actually the hexes.

00:08:24.359 --> 00:08:25.200
And as you know,

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.480
Tidyverse is all about collecting different hexes together.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:30.200
So it just makes more sense in context right now.

00:08:32.719 --> 00:08:34.159
This is my favorite one.

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:36.840
I did like AlchemFixC one time,

00:08:36.840 --> 00:08:39.359
and it's basically an carbon atom.

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:42.280
So you got like electrons and other stuff.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:45.760
But when you add one more small dots on the right,

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:48.159
it's no longer a carbon, it's a nitrogen.

00:08:48.159 --> 00:08:49.719
But nobody gonna spot it.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:50.599
But yeah.

00:08:51.559 --> 00:08:54.679
So this is where like all the small details

00:08:54.679 --> 00:08:56.760
really matters in such designs.

00:08:58.200 --> 00:09:01.520
So in summary, you get symbol, colors, and details.

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:03.200
This is what you need to focus on.

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:05.960
Without the community,

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:08.239
you are missing the really important part of the experience.

00:09:08.239 --> 00:09:10.479
So I really encourage to join the community.

00:09:12.599 --> 00:09:16.359
And hex build the community by connecting people together.

00:09:16.359 --> 00:09:19.520
And at the end, I just want to give a quick information

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:21.159
that in Appsilon,

00:09:21.159 --> 00:09:23.320
we recently did hex sticker design contest.

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:26.679
When we choose the stickers,

00:09:26.679 --> 00:09:29.280
the packages that will receive a new sticker,

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:30.840
so they can join all the design,

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:32.719
like the community with a new design.

00:09:32.719 --> 00:09:36.119
So the Tidy Polar is finished and it's ready.

00:09:36.119 --> 00:09:38.200
The one on the right, it's still in progress,

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:40.440
but I wanted to give him some recognition.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:42.320
There also gonna be one more in future,

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:45.159
and we will post it on social media soon.

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:46.280
So that's it.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:47.679
Thank you very much.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:48.679
Thank you.

00:09:48.679 --> 00:09:49.520
Thank you.

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:02.080
As a reminder, you can of course ask Slido questions.

00:10:02.919 --> 00:10:07.080
First question for you, what is your favorite hex sticker?

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:08.359
Oh, my favorite one?

00:10:08.359 --> 00:10:10.799
I should say that is Rhino.

00:10:10.799 --> 00:10:12.599
But I would say, I think it's gonna be the poor one

00:10:12.599 --> 00:10:13.440
in terms of design.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:14.760
I really love that one.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:15.599
Go ahead.

00:10:18.119 --> 00:10:18.960
Time refresh.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:25.440
And how does accessibility fit in with your color

00:10:25.440 --> 00:10:28.280
and your design and your details?

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:32.320
Okay, so with that, I always trying to,

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:34.760
so there is like a rules with contrast, for example,

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:37.359
when you really need to match contrast

00:10:37.359 --> 00:10:39.960
of a first element in the background,

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:41.840
so it's always visible.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:43.479
So basically there's like a set of rules

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:47.039
that I need to follow to just make it more accessible.

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:49.479
Thank you.

